article.description: Vickie Johnson, Cathrine Kraayeveld and Becky Hammon hit two free throws each in the final 25 seconds to lead the New York Liberty over the Washington Mystics 72-66 Tuesday night for their season-high fourth straight victory.
article.headline: Hammon leads all scorers with 20
article.linkText: Liberty win fourth straight, close gap on Fever
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- With less than two weeks remaining in the regular season, the New York Liberty are peaking at the right time.

Vickie Johnson, Cathrine Kraayeveld and Becky Hammon hit two free throws each in the final 25 seconds to lead the Liberty over the Washington Mystics 72-66 Tuesday night for their season-high fourth straight victory.

Hammon scored 20 points, Shameka Christon had 17 and Johnson 15 for New York, which won for the fifth time in six games and pulled within a half-game of second-place Indiana in the Eastern Conference.

"It's very important to make sure you're on a roll," Johnson said. "Right now, everything is clicking on the defensive as well as the offensive end. We still have things to work on, but we're doing pretty well."

Rookie of the Year candidate Temeka Johnson led Washington with 15 points, Charlotte Smith-Taylor added 14 and DeLisha Milton-Jones 13. Chasity Melvin and Alana Beard had 12 points each as the Mystics' starters accounted for all of the team's scoring.

Melvin's layup with 44 seconds remaining gave Washington a 66-64 lead before the Liberty closed with an 8-0 run.

La'Keshia Frett grabbed an offensive rebound was fouled as she made a tying layup with 25 seconds left. She missed the ensuing free throw, but Vickie Johnson got the rebound and was fouled by Smith-Taylor. Johnson hit both shots to give New York a 68-66 lead.

"Vickie made a great, great play," Mystics coach Richie Adubato said. "She has been making it for a long time."

Laurie Koehn missed a long jumper at the other end and Kraayeveld grabbed the rebound and was fouled by Smith-Taylor with 12 seconds left.

"We got some stops down the stretch when we needed to," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said. "We executed and we played the way we're capable of playing. Frett came up with that big offensive rebound and the putback. And V.J. got the missed free throw. It was a great ballgame on both ends of the ball."

Adubato said Koehn's 3-point shot was the play he called.

"That's what I was looking for," he said. "She was on the back of the rim. She had a look, she didn't make it."

Kraayeveld's free throws extended the Liberty's lead to four points, and Hammon sealed it with her foul shots 10 seconds later.

"There were a lot of different people that hit big shots for us tonight," said Hammon who topped 2,000 points for her career.

New York shot 46 percent, including 10-for-20 on 3-pointers. The Liberty have rallied from a halftime deficit in each game of their winning streak.

The Mystics lost their third straight game, and dropped 2 1/2 games behind third-place New York. They shot 49 percent, but just 4-for-17 on 3s.

Johnson hit a pair of free throws to give the Liberty a 42-41 lead 12 seconds into the second half. Washington then went on a 13-4 spurt, capped by Smith-Taylor's layup, to take an eight-point lead with just under 14 minutes left.

"We had this game in our hands," Adubato said. "We let it get away. We could have been a half a game behind New York and that game puts us 2 1/2 back."

Christon scored six points in 23 seconds with a 3-pointer and a three-point play to bring the Liberty within 54-51 with 11:28 remaining. New York had an 8-0 run, including 3s by Kraayeveld and Christon, to take a 60-58 lead with 4:53 left.

After Beard made a layup 26 seconds later to tie the game, Vickie Johnson missed two free throws with 4:11 remaining. DeLisha Milton-Jones hit a 3 and Temeka Johnson made 1-of-2 from the line to give the Mystics a 64-60 lead.

The Liberty opened 5-for-6 on 3-pointers to build a 21-12 lead 7:11 into the game.

Washington had a 7-0 run, capped by Smith-Taylor's 3 and fastbreak layup, to tie the game at 30 with 3:57 remaining in the half. Johnson's three-point play 37 seconds later gave the Mystics a 33-32 lead, their first since 2-0.

Washington led 41-40 at halftime.
